1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 Thank you very much for coming. As you can all see, it's quite an international panel that will focus on success stories from Central Eastern Europe. So I wanted to first ask you, Florian, you're looking into cover-bound research and you cover that market globally. And I was wondering what, in your view, the 2018 was as a year for the cover-bound market?

2
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:41,000
 And what the 2019 may be and how the cover-bound directive actually plays a positive or less positive role in terms of the global market and development of cover-bonds?

3
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 Okay, thank you, Jacek. I was asked yesterday already to sort of say a few words, five, six, seven, eight minutes. I think at some point you said I have as much time as I want to, which is a bit of a dangerous statement when you talk about cover-bound analysts in general. As you mentioned, I'm based in Frankfurt.

4
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:09,000
 I'm looking at this market for, gosh, I don't know how long, about 15 odd years. Not quite as long as Richard, but I'm quite a dinosaur on this market as well. Big, big nerd.

5
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:21,000
 I'm not going to talk football either because I'm German and I don't think I need to go much more into detail in that sense. I'll just try to give a broad international sort of perspective on this space.

6
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:36,000
 Because 2018 is sort of the last year and that's the main reason or main issue really. Directive is not so big of an issue these days, especially for investors. It's not an issue at all because the timeline is extending out a few years into the future.

7
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:45,000
 It's something I discuss a lot with issuers, but on the investor side, it hardly ever comes up, to be honest. Rich and I will spend a bit of time later discussing this.

8
00:01:45,000 --> 00:02:01,000
 What has been the main determining factor for how spreads have moved, how issuers have moved, how volumes have moved has essentially been QE or the, not end of it, because we're not at the end of it, but the last year of actual net additions to the purchase program.

9
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 That's been the main driver for the past four years essentially, because we've had those guys buying a lot, amassing about the share in the overall Euro benchmark market of around 40 odd percent.

10
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 So almost every second bond, if you want to sort of say and sort of stick to that mental image, is held by the guys in the big tower in Frankfurt and the various subsidiaries around the Euro system or the Euro zone.

11
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:40,000
 And they've squeezed out a lot of investors. They've squeezed spreads to very, very tight levels and essentially empowered issuers to just do whatever they wanted, really.

12
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:48,000
 They were clearly in a position of power and they just pushed investors around however they pleased.

13
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:53,000
 Now, as I said, we're approaching the end.

14
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:09,000
 But if you look at cable bonds, the actual end, so to speak, or the kickstart starting point for a bit of a normalization, that started as early as March because the Euro system quite actively told the issuers, guys, it's been brilliant over the past four years.

15
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:15,000
 You were able to rely on orders from our side that were around 50 percent of the expected issue size.

16
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:17,000
 So as an issuer, you knew half of my bond is preplaced.

17
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:19,000
 Investors knew half of that bond is preplaced.

18
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:21,000
 So execution risk is low.

19
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 So they were not happy to accept, but in the end accepted spread levels that they otherwise wouldn't have.

20
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,000
 And in March, the Euro system said, OK, guys, this has been it.

21
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,000
 It's been a brilliant ride for you, not so much for the investors.

22
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:34,000
 We'll sort of start to normalize this now.

23
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:41,000
 Our orders are not going to be 50 percent anymore, but they'll be at most 40 percent, and the emphasis being on the at most and not on the 40 percent number.

24
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 And that led to quite a bit of nervousness on the issuer side.

25
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:50,000
 It was real sort of 180 degrees as far as some psyche and psychology is concerned.

26
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,000
 You had a lot of issuance throughout the first months of the year.

27
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:00,000
 Usually you have seasonal patterns where come March and then April sort of issuance slows down after a really active start to the year.

28
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 This time there was no slowing down.

29
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 They just kept issuing and issuing and issuing.

30
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 And the result was spreads that just kept widening, widening and widening and widening.

31
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 And just to get a rough idea on some of the distance that we've covered by now in the sort of German space,

32
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:23,000
 because we mentioned a few times as the benchmark, so to speak, and the biggest or the longest or the oldest market.

33
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
 They had bonds trading in the mid swap minus 25, 26.

34
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:30,000
 They were issuing close to mid swap minus 20 at some point.

35
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 Nowadays you have them issuing in swap positive territory.

36
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:42,000
 So we've moved a good 20, 25 odd basis points, which for German or any core European covered bond is quite something.

37
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
 So I'm not saying we're in a normalized market environment again.

38
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 We're not quite there yet, but we've already covered quite a lot of ground.

39
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 And on the investor side, you can sense that as well.

40
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:56,000
 I was banging my head on doors that just wouldn't open for quite some time.

41
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 Because investors behind the door were just like, no, not interested.

42
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:01,000
 It's too expensive.

43
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 We can't trade this stuff.

44
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,000
 There's no rationale for us to have cover bonds as part of our asset allocation.

45
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 Bank treasuries preferred to rather just put the money at the ECB deposit facility and amass a huge amount of excess liquidity there.

46
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,000
 Asset managers just moved into higher risk assets.

47
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 Insurance guys yields were too low, so they just kind of tried to chase real assets lending, actual sort of infrastructure projects, etc.

48
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 And that's starting to change as well.

49
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 I'm getting meetings with people.

50
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 I had absolutely no chance of getting one.

51
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 And I would tend to think that it's not because of me personally, but just the market as it was for that period of time.

52
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 So it's normalizing on that side as well.

53
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:50,000
 Directive, as I mentioned, is for an investor too vague a concept.

54
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:54,000
 Everyone assumes it's improving our situation incrementally from where we are now.

55
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 So it's not a negative.

56
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 It's a sort of minor positive, but again, one that will not play out in 2019.

57
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:08,000
 So for people with a 12-month horizon, as far as measuring performance is concerned, it's not yet a driver.

58
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 The driver really has been QE, reducing orders.

59
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 And that's already taken place to a large extent.

60
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:19,000
 Looking into 2019, again, those factors aren't going to be much different in the end.

61
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 You will still have sizable reinvestments from the Euro system as far as APP, CBPP3, ABSPP, CSPP and PSPP is concerned.

62
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 Secondary versus secondary, so secondary buying this year versus secondary buying next year, that's probably not going to change.

63
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 That's probably going to be exactly the same in 2020 because of the maturity profile increasing in the coming years.

64
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 They might actually be back to buying almost as much as they have this year.

65
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 So that is still a supporting factor, which if I think about a country such as Gratia, you won't have the direct investment, of course,

66
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:00,000
 but you will have that as a still supportive factor in the market for quite a few years.

67
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 It doesn't say you can't have spread widening.

68
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 I mean, we did have spread widening, but it still sort of calms down or reduces the risk of any overshooting.

69
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 And for the last four years, sectors that were not in the scope of the Euro system spying did benefit from it as well,

70
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 simply because of everything being pushed down in investors trying to rebalance their portfolios to the slightly higher yielding sectors,

71
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 which they still perceive to be high quality.

72
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:35,000
 And for example, one big area of the own funds and pension fund investments by the Euro system has been non-eligible covered bonds

73
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 because they were kind of banned from buying the Euro system APP eligible assets.

74
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:43,000
 I didn't want to step on their colleagues' turf, so to speak.

75
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 There isn't much in terms of non-eligible public sector assets.

76
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:54,000
 And covered is a pretty big and chunky market in countries such as, well, Canada, Australia are big.

77
00:07:54,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 You have the Nordics, and to some extent, to a lesser extent here out in Central Eastern Europe as well.

78
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:03,000
 But that's been benefiting those markets.

79
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 And as I mentioned, we've seen one leg of repricing since March.

80
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:15,000
 We might see another one in January with issuance sort of restarting as you usually have as far as sort of normal seasonality is concerned.

81
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 But I've also mentioned that we're sort of starting to approach normality or as normal a market as you can expect with redemption reinvestment still happening in the coming few years.

82
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 Just one word on green.

83
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 As you mentioned, it is still a niche product.

84
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:41,000
 There's been a few issuers out of Germany that have used it because they fund commercial real estate lending with covered bonds.

85
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 And it's easier to identify a 50 million loan or a number of 50 million loans and assess their greenness, so to speak, than having a few thousand of retail mortgages.

86
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:57,000
 And there's not yet a clear sort of definition as to what the market or what regulators as well would consider to be green.

87
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:05,000
 There is work being done by the ECBC, EMF, so European Mortgage Federation, to sort of define a green or energy efficient mortgage.

88
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 The moment you have that, and the Commissioner, I think, is quite happy to support that as much as they can.

89
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 The moment you have that, the link from the asset side to the funding side is like this.

90
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 I mean, that's really quick.

91
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:22,000
 So, once you have that, your projections are probably going to be, even the optimistic ones, are going to be really pessimistic.

92
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:26,000
 But if you don't have that, even your pessimistic one is probably going to be really optimistic.

93
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:28,000
 Thank you very much, Florian.

94
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 And just to say, EBRD is also an advisory council of ECBC's work on green.

95
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 But you said really interesting points on the QE decreasing and how it impacts development of the market and the change, the seasonability or lack of seasons in cover bond calendar repricing.

96
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:55,000
 And then also the change of behaviour of the biggest buyer who started buying a bit less.

97
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:07,000
 I wonder how all of that, plus on the side, the cover bond directive, Thomas, you think would or may not or may have already impacted the cover bond market in Central Eastern Europe.

98
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:16,000
 Hello, well, I'm Thomas Rodriguez.

99
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 I'm a lead analyst in the Moody's for the last 10 years.

100
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 And I'm the analyst of Slovak, Czech and Turkish covered bonds amongst others.

101
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:34,000
 But yes, as Jasek has said, I'm going to give an overview on the C covered bond market.

102
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:48,000
 And, you know, sometimes it may seem that covered bonds are a new product here in the C region, but far from being so, we rated our first covered bond back in 2004 in Hungary.

103
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,000
 So almost 15 years ago.

104
00:10:51,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 And since then, we have rated covered bonds in Slovakia, in Czech Republic, in Poland, with ratings that range from BW1 now in Hungary to AA's and also, as you have mentioned before, one AAA in Slovakia.

105
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 And we are analysing some other markets like Romanian or the Pan-Valtics.

106
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:26,000
 And, you know, covered bonds are a key funding tool for housing markets and also in some of the countries of this region as well.

107
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:37,000
 Like it could be Hungary or Slovakia or Czech Republic where covered bonds may mean 20% or more of the housing loans.

108
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:42,000
 And we have seen a great development on the last years.

109
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 In fact, issuance in 2017 doubled that of 2016.

110
00:11:49,000 --> 00:12:03,000
 And there are some issuers in these countries that are considering to finance their growing mortgage loan portfolios with covered bonds.

111
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 And I think that the main factors, of course, apart from the benefits of issuing covered bonds in terms of costs and in terms of funding over longer maturities,

112
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:19,000
 and so on.

113
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:22,000
 And so, you know, we have seen the interest rate development are, first of all, the economic growth in most of the region.

114
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 So, you have seen a disposable income growing.

115
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,000
 We have seen an unemployment rate decreasing.

116
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 We have seen, well, low interest rates, no?

117
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 In the end, this makes borrowers to repay the mortgage debt quite easily.

118
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:44,000
 And this is great positive for covered bonds.

119
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:49,000
 But as well, these factors make the volume of housing loans to increase a lot.

120
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:59,000
 And we have seen in some countries, for example, Czech Republic or Poland, that the volume of housing loans has doubled in the last 10 years.

121
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 But in Slovakia or Romania, it has tripled, you know?

122
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:10,000
 And, I mean, it seems that banks need a way to finance these mortgage loan portfolios.

123
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 And the second factor, I would say that, and it has been discussed, and it will be discussed a lot here, is the harmonization of the covered bond frameworks.

124
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 We think harmonization will keep the favorable regulatory treatment for covered bonds, which is a great positive for all European covered bonds, and also here in this region.

125
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 Because we have seen some outdated legislations and also some other countries without any covered bond framework.

126
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 And we think the harmonization will keep the depth and the liquidity of the covered bond markets, which is again a very positive, no?

127
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 And, well, we also see some risks, of course.

128
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:01,000
 We see the rapid increase of some housing markets in some countries.

129
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:07,000
 We see as well a rapid increase of the house prices as well.

130
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:23,000
 We think, of course, this is negative because people will borrow more money and contribute less equity when buying a house, which is, of course, negative for new loans that enter into the covered pools in the future.

131
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:28,000
 But we have seen as well some mitigants here.

132
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 We have seen most of the countries that have developed regulatory measures that restrict leverage and also that limit loan-to values, no?

133
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 As could be, well, I mean, during the last summer we have seen Hungary, Poland, Czech Republic, Slovakia that have done so, no?

134
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 So, that is quite positive because it mitigates these risks to some extent.

135
00:14:53,000 --> 00:15:07,000
 So, I mean, in summary, yeah, what we have seen is a great development over the last years and due to harmonization and economic growth, but we still see some risks as could be the house price increase.

136
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:15,000
 Thank you very much, Thomas, and you're right, especially on the house pricing increase.

137
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:32,000
 It's been a steady few years when in Central Eastern Europe they really do grow, but also the unemployment goes down and that's a positive impact for the mortgage market development that in turn comes to also cover bond market development.

138
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:39,000
 I wanted to turn into Cuba because we've heard, or to Jakub, we've heard Poland mention a few times.

139
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:52,000
 You're representing one of the biggest mortgage cover bonds issuer, and that is a part of the biggest Polish bank group, and you basically created that market.

140
00:15:52,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 I wanted to hear a bit more about the experience in setting up and establishing the market, because a few years ago there was no cover bond market in Poland, now it's changing.

141
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:10,000
 And I wonder whether your Formula F1 Catholics that you have demonstrate the speed of change and development of that market.

142
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:12,000
 Oh, it's working?

143
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:13,000
 Working.

144
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:15,000
 So, I'm Jakub Niksłowski.

145
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:17,000
 So, actually I'm fresh to the market.

146
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:24,000
 So, taking to Richard and all Florian experience, so still I feel definitely like a freshman.

147
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:39,000
 However, as it was already indicated, we did a lot actually, so I'm responsible for the cover bond issuance, so the most, I would say, exciting thing in the mortgage bank.

148
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:49,000
 And, however, actually my more experienced colleagues are telling that due to their stability covered bonds are boring.

149
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
 But, I tend to not agree to that.

150
00:16:52,000 --> 00:17:03,000
 And, actually, it took us a few years actually to be in the place where we are currently, so pretty quick.

151
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 Because, although we had a law, what was indicated in the presentation by Andrea and Jacek, starting in 1998, however, the law was not perfect.

152
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:27,000
 So, we got two mortgage banks, or three mortgage banks, one was dissolved, but the market was dying.

153
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:33,000
 The impulse came from the new law, which was introduced January 2016.

154
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:36,000
 So, I can say that we have completely new law.

155
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:39,000
 It was really game-changer.

156
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:46,000
 And here, thanks to support of EBRD, we were able to do it, and also taking experience from other markets.

157
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:53,000
 Also, colleagues from rating agencies, we also learned from them how we should structure the law.

158
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:59,000
 That was actually one building block of our success, so new law.

159
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 Why so?

160
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:07,000
 It actually increased the safety of our covered bonds, taking into account OC level, liquidity buffers.

161
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:13,000
 But also, what is very important, opens the market for foreign investors.

162
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:21,000
 One of the barriers was withholding tax, and it was eliminated for the foreign investors.

163
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:36,000
 And also, when we created the law, what was important, not only the activities of the mortgage banks, as the entity, which are actually able to, or allowed to issue covered bonds.

164
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:40,000
 But we also took care about investors.

165
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:49,000
 So, what was also introduced, a limit, for example, for the pension funds, a separate limit for pension funds to invest in covered bonds.

166
00:18:49,000 --> 00:19:02,000
 So, it's very important, not only, I would say, create a mortgage bank or covered bond market for the issuers, but also look on the investors.

167
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 Both on the local market, it was also told by Andrea that we based on the local market, and also on the foreign market.

168
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:16,000
 So, we took care about two of them.

169
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 And so, we started with the new law.

170
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:36,000
 Then, it was very important for us to actually, as a market leader, because PKOB Group has currently around 30% of the mortgage market in Poland, which is 100 billion slots.

171
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:50,000
 So, actually, we want to be responsible and originate land responsibly, which we learn also from more experienced markets, that it means that we should have covered bonds.

172
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:55,000
 That's why our group decided to set a mortgage bank to issue covered bonds.

173
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:00,000
 So, it was strategy, but strategy decision.

174
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 But what was important, and again, it was already mentioned, so I don't want to repeat too much, economics.

175
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:12,000
 So, simply, the financing with covered bonds is cheaper than senior unsecured.

176
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:20,000
 And our group, our banking group, actually replaced existing senior funding with cheaper covered bond funding.

177
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:28,000
 Both from the European market, as we are issuing in Euro, and swapping to Polish lotte, and the Euro is taken by the mother company.

178
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:36,000
 And they are simply replacing their existing financing in currency to financing with covered bonds.

179
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:47,000
 And also financing from the local market, which we also are ready to obtain at much better price than the senior unsecured.

180
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:55,000
 So, that is actually also strategy, but also economics.

181
00:20:55,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 And here Richard mentioned in the presentation that roughly 30% of the mortgages are financed with covered bonds.

182
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:08,000
 That's one of the goals which we have on the Polish market, we also as a group.

183
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:14,000
 Yes, so now as a market, we are on the 5% level.

184
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:18,000
 We as a group are more at the 15% level.

185
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:24,000
 So, still a lot to go, but we are, I would say, determined to do it.

186
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:28,000
 Because we see importance of covered bonds.

187
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:31,000
 Responsibility, but also economics here.

188
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 And yes, so this Formula 1 will go further, definitely.

189
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:41,000
 So, we look on the one hand, further plans to issue.

190
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:48,000
 So, what is important for the investors to be a regular issuer of covered bonds.

191
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:56,000
 So, it's our commitment, which means for us that we will be present each year on the market with at least one Euro benchmark transaction,

192
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:58,000
 which means minimum 500 million.

193
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:02,000
 But also, we do care about our local investors.

194
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:09,000
 So, here concerning, I would say local investors, what was needed from us, a lot of educations.

195
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:14,000
 So, I got a lot of meetings with the investors to present them covered bonds.

196
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:16,000
 Actually, what is it?

197
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 And what's actually worth to buy it?

198
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:23,000
 Yes, for the more safe part of the portfolio.

199
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:26,000
 Yes, invest and forget about it.

200
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:30,000
 And take care about more risky investments.

201
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:33,000
 So, that was important.

202
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:40,000
 And what was mentioned, finishing words concerning green, because it will also rise during the presentation.

203
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:45,000
 I don't think Formula 1 and green go hand by hand.

204
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:46,000
 Yeah.

205
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:48,000
 So, that's good.

206
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:51,000
 That gives us a lot of comfort, actually.

207
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:57,000
 Because, here we do see importance also to be on the green covered bond market.

208
00:22:57,000 --> 00:22:59,000
 It's expanding.

209
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:03,000
 Both here, we'll also look on the European, but also on the local market.

210
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:04,000
 It got some challenges.

211
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:07,000
 For example, identification of green assets.

212
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:14,000
 And also, introducing offer for green financing for the customers.

213
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 But, why we are doing it?

214
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:24,000
 Because, we do not see for now, I would say, visible difference in cost of financing.

215
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:31,000
 But, what we do see is that investors creating or have green pockets.

216
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:34,000
 And, we want to get to these pockets.

217
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:41,000
 Because, it actually leads to extending of investors' base.

218
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:43,000
 So, we are now on the preparatory stage.

219
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:45,000
 We are creating the framework.

220
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:52,000
 And, our plan is to be on the green, also green covered bond market next year.

221
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:55,000
 Thank you very much, Jakub, for that and for the statement.

222
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:00,000
 We will take it on record for the next year, covered bond, green covered bond coming out of Poland.

223
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:06,000
 You touch upon some really important points, but one which is very relevant, I think, also for Croatia.

224
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:10,000
 We look into international investors, but we also look into domestic investors.

225
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:16,000
 And, if you look into domestic capital market here, pension funds play a big, big role in investing into capital markets.

226
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:21,000
 And, that's something that on the investor limit, we also made sure that in the draft law is being addressed.

227
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:25,000
 So, it allows for the investment in cover bond as an instrument.

228
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:38,000
 And, that brings me to Richard, to talk about completely different success stories on the first ever triple A bond issued in the BRD country of operations.

229
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:44,000
 So, I wonder, how was it to prepare to align your operations and your business with the new law?

230
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:46,000
 How difficult that was?

231
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:48,000
 And, how were your discussions with the investors?

232
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:52,000
 And, then we'll come back to Andra on the international investor perspective.

233
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:53,000
 Okay.

234
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:54,000
 Hello, everybody.

235
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:59,000
 My name is Richard Koschecki from Slovenska Sporytelnia, RST Group.

236
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:06,000
 I wouldn't say that it's a completely different story, because I see quite a lot of similarities to the Polish story.

237
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:09,000
 So, it's a step-by-step process.

238
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:12,000
 So, it always starts with the legislation.

239
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:17,000
 In our case, it started in 2016, I would say, the first discussions.

240
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:21,000
 And, the law became alive in 2000, beginning of 2018.

241
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:25,000
 So, it took two years to set up the legal framework.

242
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:32,000
 With regard to the rating, we started, I would say, like one year ago, preparing our covered bond program.

243
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:38,000
 What was important for us, we put quite a lot of effort into that.

244
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 So, we would like to prepare the portfolio, the loan, the assets, which are very clean, very conservative portfolios.

245
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:50,000
 So, only residential mortgages, no FX loans.

246
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:56,000
 Very, very, very clean portfolio with a nice seasoning, with a nice LTV, and so on and so forth.

247
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 So, we were expecting quite a nice result out of it.

248
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:04,000
 And, actually, we got the best result, which was the AAA rating.

249
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:09,000
 Of course, big success, but I would say a lot of work behind.

250
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:14,000
 I would mention, also, maybe the work on the bank itself.

251
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:16,000
 You need to have, really, the infrastructure.

252
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:22,000
 So, you need to have the policies, the workflows, and, at the end, the data in place.

253
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:26,000
 When I checked what is really required, I was quite surprised.

254
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:30,000
 For each loan, or each transaction, we need almost 200 fields.

255
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:39,000
 So, 200 different, like, data, like, about the customers, about the credit, about the income, and so on and so forth.

256
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:49,000
 So, to fulfilling the requirements of the national bank, or for the regulator, rating agency, we need to have around 200 fields for each transaction.

257
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:56,000
 What was great was that we had those data, but, as you know, there are always different places, different data marts.

258
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:01,000
 So, we had to do quite a lot of work to put the data into one centralized place.

259
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:11,000
 And, currently, we have it. We can produce quite regularly the data on very frequent basis, at least on the monthly basis.

260
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:14,000
 And, for the future, we would like to do it on the daily basis.

261
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:25,000
 What changed from the business perspective was, it was already mentioned here, that we always had to fulfill these minimum financing ratios, which was the case before.

262
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:36,000
 So, any time when the loan portfolio increased by something, we had to immediately issue the transaction, the covered bond, which was obviously the very low, very small ticket.

263
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:44,000
 And the small ticket means that you don't have diversified investors, that the liquidity, secondary market liquidity is very poor, and so on and so forth.

264
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 So, in July this year, we received the license from the national bank, fulfilling all the criterias.

265
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:55,000
 We have an independent cover pool monitor or administrator.

266
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:58,000
 We received the rating, and we did our first transaction.

267
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:03,000
 And the first transaction was in the amount of 250 million, which was, for us, like a dream.

268
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:11,000
 Before, we always did, like, 30, 40 million transactions, which was very costly, no liquidity, and so on and so forth.

269
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:13,000
 So, we did the transaction.

270
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:20,000
 We tracked mostly local investors from Slovakia and Austria, and we did a quite attractive level.

271
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:25,000
 So, we did a seven-year bond with plus 12 basis points.

272
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:30,000
 For us, of course, it's cost efficient.

273
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:37,000
 And comparing to the maybe German market, you see that there is always some pickup, but what is the reason?

274
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:46,000
 I would say the main reason is that it's still, it's Slovakia, there is certain spread of Slovak Gavis versus the German Gavis, and plus the liquidity.

275
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:49,000
 I still have to say the secondary market liquidity is not ideal.

276
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:56,000
 So, there is a certain pickup or spread add-on due to the liquidity of this bond.

277
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:58,000
 So, it happened.

278
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:02,000
 We have a AAA rating, but there is still quite a lot of work to do.

279
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:13,000
 As Jakub said, we would like to attract foreign investors to go more to the West, to the Germany, maybe to Baltics, Nordics, and so on.

280
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:22,000
 And hopefully, we will achieve also from the not just perfect credit and safe investment, but also something which is quite liquid and so on.

281
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:23,000
 Thank you, Richard.

282
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:28,000
 I have a follow-up question from your experience with the 250 million issuance.

283
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:31,000
 Who are the investors geographically that were really interested?

284
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:35,000
 Was it mostly domestic or you had some of the internationals coming to your door as well?

285
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:37,000
 Or you coming to their doors?

286
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:39,000
 For me, it was local market.

287
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:43,000
 For me, local market means Slovakia, Austria.

288
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:46,000
 So, basically, these two countries.

289
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:51,000
 From the type of investors, mostly banks and the pension funds.

290
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:54,000
 So, a little bit of insurance companies.

291
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:58,000
 And then, of course, the supranational institutions like Central Bank.

292
00:29:58,000 --> 00:29:59,000
 Thank you.

293
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:00,000
 Thank you for that.

294
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:06,000
 You said something which was really nice, that the 250 million euro bond issuance was a dream for you.

295
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:13,000
 Sandra, when you look into cover bond investment and decide what you would like to buy as a bank or not.

296
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:18,000
 What is the dream and what is not a dream come true looking into the investment side?

297
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:27,000
 Well, I mean, we are a development bank, but when you look at the investment in cover bonds, we have a commercial perspective as well.

298
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:30,000
 So, we are looking at different things.

299
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:35,000
 So, first of all, I mean, of course, the legislation has to be there.

300
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:39,000
 And it has to meet the criteria as we discussed.

301
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:41,000
 The legislation is not there.

302
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:45,000
 As we've seen, we amend or we create the legislation.

303
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:52,000
 But once we have a law, we like to work with the issuance, you know, targeting the first time the markets.

304
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:58,000
 And we support -- we like to be there for them at first when they go for the first time to the market.

305
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:03,000
 What we've seen is mostly initially on the local market.

306
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:07,000
 It was set there, which we believe is very important to develop the local capital market.

307
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:09,000
 It's one of the strategy for EPRT.

308
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:14,000
 So, supporting the first time insurers on the local market is part of their objectives.

309
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:26,000
 We act as a corner store investor, as we like to say, in the sense that we can take up to 20% of issuances, of course, subject to the final terms when they are available.

310
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:32,000
 So, we have certain requirements in terms of, you know, the investment criteria.

311
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:37,000
 We require our investments to -- investments in -- I mean, the issuance has to be rated.

312
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:40,000
 This is one of the -- of the criteria.

313
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:43,000
 We can't invest in the unrated covered bonds.

314
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:49,000
 We believe that this is very important for developing of a covered market to have rating.

315
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:58,000
 We've seen in some of our markets, especially on the -- on the small -- small type of issuance, that the local investors, they don't require a rating.

316
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:04,000
 For us, it's very important to have a rated program.

317
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:06,000
 We don't have a certain minimum rating.

318
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:14,000
 As I mentioned before, Greece is one of the -- probably the best example where we invested in a B -- a single B covered bond.

319
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:23,000
 So, we don't have a -- you know, we don't require a minimum investment rate as long as it's rated by one of the -- of the -- of the three rating agencies.

320
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:27,000
 In terms of size of the issuance, we are quite flexible.

321
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:32,000
 But it has to be, obviously, commensurate with the -- you know, with the size of the -- of the local market.

322
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:36,000
 We don't require to feed -- to be a sub-benchmarked 250 million.

323
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:40,000
 I mean, in Poland, the first one we invested, I remember, was 500 million slots.

324
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:43,000
 So, about 120 million euro equivalent.

325
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:48,000
 So, it depends on the -- you know, on the size of the -- the respecting market.

326
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:59,000
 ECB eligibility -- because most of our countries are not in Eurozone, the -- the cover bonds we invested were not part of the cover bond purchase program.

327
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:04,000
 Except for Greece, that it was initially and then it was -- it was not.

328
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:07,000
 So, we don't -- we don't require to -- to be part of it.

329
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:10,000
 Of course, you know, if it's an ECB-eligible bond, it helps.

330
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:17,000
 We -- we require, you know, transparency and disclosure.

331
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:19,000
 It's very important for us.

332
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:27,000
 There are some initiatives, as you know, from the ECBC in terms of the transparency template.

333
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:31,000
 We like to see proper disclosure to the investors.

334
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:39,000
 Unfortunately, this is an area that in some of our markets is not -- because it's not -- the regulators, they don't -- they don't require this.

335
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:43,000
 And, you know, we -- we work with the issuers towards this.

336
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:47,000
 Because we -- we really like to see, you know, proper disclosure to investors.

337
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:52,000
 So, you know, everybody has -- has access to -- to the information.

338
00:33:52,000 --> 00:33:59,000
 And the -- the directivity, it helps from this -- from this point of view.

339
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:05,000
 In terms of liquidity, I mean, we are -- you know, whereas, you know, any other cover bond investor --

340
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:09,000
 also, we have maybe a longer-term horizon than others.

341
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:15,000
 But we like to see some liquidity, some, you know, market-making activity for the -- for the cover bonds we invest.

342
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:19,000
 Also, we -- we are aware that in some of our markets, it's -- it's quite difficult.

343
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:26,000
 I mean, Richard mentioned Slovakia, actually, which was one of the examples where, although we've seen some sub-benchmark issues recently,

344
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:34,000
 if you look on the -- you know, the liquidity on the -- on the cover bonds, traded locally, it's -- it's not that high.

345
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:35,000
 Thank you.

346
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:36,000
 And the currency side?

347
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:39,000
 Well, we have access to local currency.

348
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:45,000
 So, we are -- we have appetite to -- to -- to invest in -- in local currency as well.

349
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:51,000
 So, we invested in -- we invested in -- in the Hungarian foreign.

350
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:55,000
 So, we -- we are basically -- we are flexible from this point of view.

351
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:58,000
 And actually, we like more local currency.

352
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:01,000
 I mean, this is what you wanted to hear.

353
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:04,000
 Sir, I'm from local currency, local capital market team.

354
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:08,000
 So, we -- we prefer to -- you know, to invest in local currency.

355
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:12,000
 But we are also, you know, aware that, you know, for the -- to attract the international investors,

356
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:16,000
 it has to be an, you know, euro benchmark issuances.

357
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:17,000
 Thank you very much, Andra.

358
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:23,000
 Before I give a floor to all of you for -- for concluding remarks, I wanted to check whether any one of you in the audience,

359
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:30,000
 and also looking into creation market in the back of the room has any questions or points that we would like to hear a bit more

360
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:35,000
 or we can elaborate on that may be relevant to, hopefully, your future business.

361
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:40,000
 Don't worry, I'm not putting you on the spot.

362
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:45,000
 There is also a coffee break that we can network and go in the next five minutes.

363
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:50,000
 But before that, I wanted to look into the panelists and see whether you have any concluding remarks,

364
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:56,000
 comments, agreements or disagreements to whatever else -- everyone else mentioned in your discussion.

365
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:59,000
 Flora, you look like you want to say something.

366
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:08,000
 No, I just wanted to -- because I was sort of brought on this panel to get a bit of an international perspective as well --

367
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:17,000
 because Andreas talked about how she looks at investment, which is perfectly fair and well for the purposes that you guys have,

368
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:21,000
 but it's not necessarily identical to how international investors would look at cover bonds.

369
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:28,000
 I mean, the focus on framework, on policy, on supporting, in your case, is much bigger than it would be the case for,

370
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:33,000
 let's say, a eurozone bank or a German asset manager.

371
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:35,000
 There, it really starts with the sovereign.

372
00:36:35,000 --> 00:36:38,000
 If they're fine with that, then they go any deeper.

373
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:42,000
 If they're not fine with that, most frequently they would just kind of stop the process there.

374
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:48,000
 And then next comes the issuer, because we're talking about bonds are issued by financial institutions.

375
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:55,000
 I mean, the framework on collateral is all nice and well, but you don't really, really ever want to rely on that

376
00:36:55,000 --> 00:37:00,000
 if you're an asset manager or, in general, an investor in cover bond space.

377
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:02,000
 And then comes the framework and then comes the collateral.

378
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:09,000
 So it really starts with the sovereign and then sort of trickles down into the pool at the end of the day.

379
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:17,000
 Size-wise, you have those thresholds where it starts with 250 million when sort of bank treasuries start to pay a bit more attention

380
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:19,000
 because these bonds are then LCR eligible.

381
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:24,000
 For an asset manager, it's essentially 500 plus unless you really pay up spread-wise.

382
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:27,000
 And for the insurance guys, I mean, they look at private placements.

383
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:32,000
 And there, the bigger issue is, can issuers actually provide them with long enough duration?

384
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:38,000
 Because in many cases, yes, it just wouldn't be long enough to issue 20, 25 year private placements.

385
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:41,000
 So it's a slightly different angle than what you mentioned.

386
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:47,000
 Having a domestic currency investor base always helps to be completely delinked from your local.

387
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:57,000
 So the market is always seen as a bit of a not so ideal because ultimately the ones supporting the most in times of stress are going to be the ones that know these institutions best.

388
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:00,000
 And that's ultimately the local currency or the domestic guys.

389
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:04,000
 But it's not an absolute binary requirement.

390
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:06,000
 If there's no local market, then people don't buy.

391
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:10,000
 I mean, we have quite a few examples where issuers use cover bonds to expand into different currencies.

392
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:14,000
 And the local currency stuff is issued in senior or non-preferred or sub.

393
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:16,000
 So it's a bit of a different angle.

394
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:17,000
 Thank you.

395
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:19,000
 Thank you for that and getting us the market background.

396
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:20,000
 Kuba.

397
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:35,000
 Just to comment that from my experience, I totally agree that we actually sell Poland starting from the micro view banking sector and then we come up to the actually bank itself and the cover pool.

398
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:47,000
 But another, I would say, point is that the foreign investors, let's say German investors, they are investors who are investing in covered bonds from many, many, many years.

399
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:53,000
 And they know the questions and what they want to know.

400
00:38:53,000 --> 00:39:02,000
 And if you convince them, then they, that's my experience, at least after four benchmark issues, they are constantly buying your covered bonds.

401
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:10,000
 So from this point of view, sometimes discussion is, I would say, more easy than with local investors.

402
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:15,000
 Because this is what I actually mentioned, that it needs a lot of education.

403
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:22,000
 In Poland, we do not have, for example, analysts which take, which actually take care of covered bonds.

404
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:24,000
 So we have to educate people.

405
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:25,000
 What is investors?

406
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:29,000
 And, of course, why we are paying not so much.

407
